Findings of 1990

The following variables are selected to see if the difference in income between men and women in 1990 vary depending on them:

  1. race
  2. age.start.alcohol.1984
  3. womens.roles.q1
  4. womens.roles.q2
  5. family.size.1979

T-Test

Use t.test to test if there is significant difference in income between male and female in 1990.

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  income.1990 by gender
## t = -22.674, df = 5380.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -8634.298 -7260.077
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             11889.45             19836.63

The outcome shows that the average different in income between male and female in 1990 is 7947 dollar, with the p value 0, which is very significant.

Model 1

In the first model, only the data of those whose income is more than 0 but not top coded is used to do linear regression. The whole cleaned data frame is divided into two parts, one male and one female, and regression seperately.

Test if income is normally distributed using qqplot.

It looks like the data is not normally distributed.

Divide the data frame into 2 parts according to gender.

First test if there are collinear variables in male.

From the plot, it can be seen that no variables are collinear in male.

Then test female.

From the plot, no variables are collinear in female.

So it it safe to do linear regression.

From the 2 tables, it is found that the difference in income in 1990 vary depending on:
1. Race. The income of people of different races have significant different income. The income of Hispanic male is 3438.340054 more than Black male which is the base line, while that of Hispanic female is only 2001.2434211 more than Black female. It means that difference in income of Hispanic is 1437.0966329 more than difference of Black. Similarly, difference of Other races is 3778.3096291 more.
2. First age of alcohol consumption. This variable can significantly influence female with the p value 0.0467693, and every year later of starting drinking, 55.3289475 more income she will have. But this variable of male is not significant, only with the p value 0.1365389 .
3. Whether the responder agrees that a wife who carries out her full family responsibilities does not have time for outside employment (women.role.2). The difference between those who disagree narrows 643.0078721. The difference between those who strongly disagree is even more, which is 262.479107.
4. Family size. This variable can significantly influence male with the p value 0.0017992, and every one more person in family, 321.3212891 less income he will have. But this variable of female is not significant, only with the p value 0.5299491.

It is found that whether one has top 2% income in 1990 vary depending on:
1. Race. For male of other race compared to black, the odds of having an income of top 2% increase by a factor of 1.0195323 with a p value of 0.0258885, while there is no significant relationship between female of other race and black female.

For male who strongly disagree with it compared to male who agree with it, the odds of having an income of top 2% increase by a factor of 1.0428291 with a p value of 0.0124462, while there is no significant relationship for that of female.

Interaction Model

Here we use interaction model to study how the difference in income between male and female varies depending on other factors. Three different models are introduced to respectively depict three income variables in different years.

For the income in 1990, all the variables mentioned above related to year 1990 are taken into consideration here at first. We select the variabels needed into clean.nlsy.income1990.4. For the income of 1990, we exclude the top 2% and zero income data.

To test whether the income.1990 in clean.nlsy.income1990.4 is normally distributed, qqmorm() and qqline() are used here.

From the figure above, income.1990^0.5 (left one) is more normally distributed than income.1990 (right one). Therefore, income.1990^0.5 is used in this interaction regression model.

Make each variable interact with gender. The summary and plots are as follows:

Be careful that the dependant variable here is income.1990^0.5 rather than income.1990, so the interperation of the coefficients will be different.

According to the results, generally, the income.1990^0.5 of male will be 32.85 higher than female. Therefore, the income difference between male and female in 1990 is 6987.39

There are two interaction terms indicate the significant association to the difference of income between male and female.

  • genderMale:raceOther: the Other race significantly incluence the income difference between male and femal. In Other race, the difference of income.1990^0.5 between male and femal increases 13.1. Therefore, the income difference between male and femal in Other race will increase 4380.67.

  • genderMale:womens.roles.q2Strongly disagree: for male and female who Strongly disagree with the question Wife with family has no time for other employment?, their difference of income.1990^0.5 decreases 7.14.

  • genderMale:womens.roles.q2Disagree: for male and female who Disagree with the question Wife with family has no time for other employment?, their difference of income.1990^0.5 decreases 5.15.
